data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. Here's the full migration:

## What breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(work, timeout, cts.Token);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(cancellationToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when
            // the token fires, even if Task.Run's delegate is still
            // running — this gives us timeout behavior.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch for

**1. The work doesn't magically stop.** Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` is a CPU-bound loop, it keeps running in the background after timeout. To fix this, pass the token into the delegate:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveWork(cts.Token),  // check token inside
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. Inside long-running work, check the token regularly:**

```csharp
void ExpensiveWork(CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
}
```

**3. Replace blocking calls that ignore cancellation:**

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) |
|----------------------|--------------|
| `Thread.Sleep(ms)` | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| `stream.Read(...)` | `await stream.ReadAsync(..., token)` |

**4. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaking it leaks the internal timer. The `using` statement above handles this.

**5. Truly uncooperative code** (third-party library, native call) cannot be cancelled with a token. The only safe option is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout.

## If you can go fully async (recommended)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(cancellationToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

This version passes the token directly into the work delegate, giving the best cooperative cancellation and no orphaned background threads.
